                                <p class="profile-position">
                                    Multiple sclerosis is a condition in which there is damage to the covering of nerves in the brain or spinal cord. This damage is due to attack on these nervous structure by body’s immune response. Some patients can experience repeated attacks of Multiple sclerosis and some patients can have more progressive course with gradual decline in neurologic function. The symptoms are variable and can be in isolation or combination. These include: Vision loss, imbalance, weakness, difficulty in standing and walking, loss of control over urination, numbness and pain in some cases. The symptoms are worse during fever or stressful conditions. The diagnosis of multiple sclerosis is made by Neurologist by detailed assessment of patient and investigations. There have been many advances in the last decade in the treatment of multiple sclerosis. As a result the disease has become manageable and many patients with multiple sclerosis can live an independent and symptom free life.
                                </p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
